// The `prelude.http` sub-module: a built-in HTTP client. `fetch` is an `external` whose calls route to the
// runtime's `http` reactor (an in-runtime `fetch`, not an FFI sidecar) via the `from "http"` clause. It is
// called as `http.fetch`.
//
// Because it is an external call it performs io: the call is impure (it carries the un-dischargeable `io`
// effect, which propagates to the run root), so it takes the strict, non-lifting call path. That gives the
// information-flow rules for free: `url` / `method` / `body` are public `string`, so a secret cannot be sent
// in a URL or body (a private value there is a type error — a secret must not go outbound); only header
// *values* are `string of private` (a secret may be sent as an auth header); and the response is public
// (declassified — it is the server's response, not a function of the secret).
//
// Errors: a non-2xx response is returned as its `status` to branch on (`match (response.status) { ... }`).
// A request that never completes (DNS failure, refused connection, timeout, or a mid-flight restart) throws
// `fetch_error`, which bubbles from the call site to the nearest handler — so a caller can `use handler {
// request throw(error: http.fetch_error) -> never { break ... } }` to handle the failure locally and
// control retry.

@"An HTTP request never completed: DNS failure, refused connection, timeout, or a mid-flight runtime
restart. Thrown by `fetch`. (A response that did arrive is never an error — branch on its `status`.)"
data fetch_error(message: string)

@"Perform an HTTP request to @url@ with @method@ (e.g. \"GET\" / \"POST\"), the given @headers@ (each value
may be a secret, such as an auth token), and @body@. Returns the response @status@ code, its @headers@
(names lowercased; repeated headers joined with \", \") and its @body@ text. A request that never
completes throws `fetch_error` (catchable with `use handler { request throw(error: http.fetch_error) ->
never { ... } }`)."
external agent fetch(
  url: string,
  method: string,
  headers: record[string of private],
  body: string,
) -> { status: integer, headers: record[string], body: string } with prelude.throw[fetch_error] from "http"

@"A JSON API responded with a non-2xx status. Thrown by `post_json` (the raw `fetch` never treats an
arrived response as an error — this wrapper takes the opinionated JSON-API stance)."
data status_error(status: integer, body: string)

@"POST @body@ to @url@ as application/json with one auth header @auth_header_name: <auth_prefix><api_key>@
(e.g. \"Authorization\" / \"Bearer \" for OpenAI, \"x-goog-api-key\" / \"\" for Gemini). Returns the
response body text; a non-2xx status throws `status_error`, a transport failure `fetch_error`. The
canonical one-call shape of a JSON API integration — build the body as `json` in Katari, post it, parse
the reply as `json` in Katari."
agent post_json(
  url: string,
  body: string,
  auth_header_name: string,
  auth_prefix: string,
  api_key: string of private,
) -> string with io | prelude.throw[status_error | fetch_error] {
  let headers = record.set(
    target = record.set(target = record.empty(), key = "Content-Type", value = "application/json"),
    key = auth_header_name,
    value = auth_prefix ++ api_key,
  )
  let response = fetch(url = url, method = "POST", headers = headers, body = body)
  if (response.status >= 200 && response.status < 300) {
    response.body
  } else {
    prelude.throw(error = status_error(status = response.status, body = response.body))
  }
}
